It
is
certain
that
about

kinds

birds

seen

in
the
spring

summer

set
down
in

A
somewhat
smaller

variety
of
birds
are
seen
in
England
only
during
the
winter.

It
is
well
known
also
to
bird-catchers,
who
only
look
after
the

males,
on
account
of
their
song,
that
the
vernal
male
birds

make
their
appearance
about
a
fortnight
before
the
females.

Of
the
birds
which
remain
in
England
during
the
whole
year,

several
species
perform
limited
migrations
from
one
part
of

the
country
to
another
at
particular
seasons.
The
poets
have

many
allusions
to
these
migrations
of
birds
by
what
Milton

calls
their
"
airy
caravans."
Timon,
in
Shakspeare,
re

proaches
his
flatterers
by
the
name
of
"
summer-birds
;"
and

the
prophet
Jeremiah
notices, — "
The
stork
in
the
heaven

knoweth
her
appointed
times
;
and
the
turtle-dove,
and
the

crane,
and
the
swallow

the
times

their
coming."
